  <!-- About Section -->
<div class="w3-main" style="margin-left:50px">
  <div class="w3-container w3-padding-32" id="about">
    <h1 class="w3-border-light-grey w3-padding-16">about</h1>
   	<h3>Early Vedic</h3>
	<h5>is the oldest attested Indo-Aryan language. Early Vedic is famous for its unique oral tradition (see <a href="#introduction"><b>introduction</b></a>).
	Its importance for the reconstruction of Proto-Indo-European can hardly be overestimated. It is the only IE language preserving breathy voiced consonants, traditionally represented as voiced aspirated. Its sandhi phenomena allow for glimpses into prosodic structure quite unexpected for a dead language (see <a href="#sounds"><b>sounds</b></a>).
	Vedic has an archaic and rich case system (see <a href="#words"><b>words</b></a>) and a complex pattern of finite and infinite embedding (see <a href="#structures"><b>structures</b></a>).
	</h5><br>

	<h3>Lecturers</h3>
		<h4><a href="https://en.uit.no/ansatte/person?p_document_id=363903", target="_blank">Eystein Dahl</a> </h4>
		<p class="w3-opacity">University of Tromsø</p>
		<h4><a href="http://www.keydana.de/index.php", target="_blank">Götz Keydana</a> </h4>
		<p class="w3-opacity">University of Göttingen</p>
		<h4><a href="https://uzh.academia.edu/TimFelixAufderheide", target="_blank">Tim Felix Aufderheide</a> </h4>
		<p class="w3-opacity">University of Jena</p>

  </div>

